eld code="e">author.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="1" ind2="4" tag="245"><subfield code="a">The birth of hedonism :</subfield><subfield code="b">the Cyrenaic philosophers and pleasure as a way of life /</subfield><subfield code="c">Kurt Lampe.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2="1" tag="264"><subfield code="a">Princeton, New Jersey :</subfield><subfield code="b">Princeton University Press,</subfield><subfield code="c">[2015]</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="300"><subfield code="a">xvii, 277 pages ;</subfield><subfield code="c">25 cm</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="336"><subfield code="a">text</subfield><subfield code="2">rdacontent</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="337"><subfield code="a">unmediated</subfield><subfield code="2">rdamedia</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="338"><subfield code="a">volume</subfield><subfield code="2">rdacarrier</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="500"><subfield code="a">Revised PhD dissertation.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="504"><subfield code="a">Includes bibliographical references (pages 263-274) and index.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="505"><subfield code="a">Introduction -- Cyrene and the Cyrenaics: a historical and biographical overview -- Knowledge and pleasure -- Virtue and living pleasantly -- Eudaimonism and anti-eudaimonism -- Personal and political relationships -- Hegesias's pessimism -- Theodorus's innovations -- The "new Cyrenaicism" of Walter Pater -- Conclusion: The birth of hedonism.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1="0" ind2=" " tag="520"><subfield code="a">According to Xenophon, Socrates tried to persuade his associate Aristippus to moderate his excessive indulgence in wine, women, and food, arguing that only hard work can bring happiness. Aristippus wasn't convinced. Instead, he and his followers espoused the most radical form of hedonism in ancient Western philosophy. Before the rise of the better known but comparatively ascetic Epicureans, the Cyrenaics pursued a way of life in which moments of pleasure, particularly bodily pleasure, held the highest value. In The Birth of Hedonism, Kurt Lampe provides the most comprehensive account in any language of Cyrenaic ideas and behavior, revolutionizing the understanding of this neglected but important school of philosophy.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="596"><subfield code="a">16</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2="0" tag="650"><subfield code="a">Hedonism.</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2="0" tag="650"><subfield code="a">Cyrenaics (Greek philosophy)</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="949"><subfield code="a">B 279 L36 2015</subfield><subfield code="c">1</subfield><subfield code="h">UAAU-B</subfield><subfield code="i">0162035220472</subfield></datafield><datafield ind1=" " ind2=" " tag="926"><subfield code="a">B 279 L36 2015</subfield><subfield code="w">LC</subfield><subfield code="c">1</subfield><subfield code="i">0162034576932</subfield><subfield code="l">ON_SHELF</subfield><subfield code="m">UAAUG</subfield><subfield code="p">$150.00</subfield><subfield code="r">Y</subfield><subfield code="s">Y</subfield><subfield code="t">BOOK</subfield><subfield code="u">1/14/2015</subfield></datafield></record>